<br>
Now, the latest developments.  North Korea has announced that it has started reprocessing fuel rods for the production of nuclear weapons, insisting that the Iraqi war proves how important those types of weapons are for security (you won't see me arguing the validity of that statement; I doubt we would have attacked Iraq if they had the Russian nuclear arsenal at their disposal).  Everyone seemed to be moving towards the consensus (or perhaps the illusion) that North Korea would verifiably disarm in exchange for a non-agression or similar pact with the U.S. and the resumption of aid.  Now, it appears that the U.S. may pull out of the talks all together.  In which case, if there is still a standstill, U.S. military action may become necessary against North Korea.  Ugh.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/2959017.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world...959017.stm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
I am really torn on what to do now.  It seems they have zero intention of ever disarming.  If they start cranking out nuclear weapons, it will be a short matter of time before those are out on the market to the highest bidder (like every other weapon/missile they produce).  That is something we cannot let happen.  I am wondering if talks will just be futile and either we accept that they will go nuclear and try to welcome them to the international community in an effort to make them more responsible or attack them before they make too many nuclear weapons.  I don't like either choice but may lean towards the latter.<br>
<br>
